---
import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import Link from '../../components/Link.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';
const title = 'Citizen Asset Creation - Cities Skylines Modding';
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import { images } from '../../data/imageImports.js';
---

<MainLayout title={title}>
	<TableOfContents />
	<section class="py-12 text-lg sm:ml-64 xl:mr-64 text-hit-gray-500">
		<h1 id="overview" class="pb-8 text-4xl font-bold border-b-4 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400">
			Citizen Asset Creation
		</h1>
		<div class="content">
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="mesh">
				Mesh
			</h2>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="main-mesh">
				Main Mesh
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">This is a 3D model of the citizen, which will be visible when the camera is close to it.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				It's created using 3D modeling software such as Blender, 3ds Max, Maya or SketchUp.<br />The actual mesh
				file contains vertices (their coordinates, UV mapping, normals, and colors) and triangles. For citizens,
				this also contains the skeleton bones to which the mesh is bound to using bone weights.
			</p>
			<h4
				class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12"
				id="model-complexity"
			>
				Model Complexity
			</h4>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						It's recommended to stay within reasonable triangle counts based on the size and detail of your
						model. You may look at examples of vanilla citizens or assets by other creators for reference.
					</p><p class="mt-4">The absolute limit for a mesh is 65536 vertices.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/citizen/citvanilla.jpg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.citvanilla.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.citvanilla}
							alt="Main model and LOD of a vanilla citizen"
							class="w-full h-auto"
							loading="eager"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Main model and LOD of a vanilla citizen.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="flex items-start justify-start gap-2 mt-6">
				<svg
					class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						You can use <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=453956891"
							text="Mesh Info by SamsamTS"
							theme="externallink"
						/> to check triangle counts of assets.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="lod-mesh">
				LOD Mesh
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				LOD stands for level of detail. This is the mesh visible from a distance. It must be as simple as
				possible. Citizens are small and the LOD is only visible very far away, so a model under 100 triangles
				could be enough.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">The LOD is not animated, so you don't need to import a skeleton for it.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="skeleton">
				Skeleton
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						You must fit your mesh to one of the available skeleton templates, which can be found in this
						folder:
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						<span class="path"
							>C:\Program FilesResponsiveImage
							(x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\Cities_Skylines\Files\Templates</span
						>
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						You need to bind your mesh to the bones of the skeleton, in 3ds Max this is done using the skin
						modifier and adding all the bones
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/citizen/citskeleton.jpg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.citskeleton.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.citskeleton}
							alt="One of the skeleton templates"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">One of the skeleton templates.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="uv-mapping"
			>
				UV Mapping
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						For the main mesh, you are allowed to UV map outside the 0-1 area (main tile), so you can tile
						the entire texture multiple times on a single face.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/uv_main.jpg" target="_blank"
						><Picture
							width={images.uv_main.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.uv_main}
							alt="Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example UV mapping using visible horizontal tiling on the bottom.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h4
				class="pb-4 mt-8 text-xl font-medium border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-950 lg:mt-12"
				id="uv-mapping-lod"
			>
				LOD
			</h4>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						For the LOD mesh, the UV mapping must be within the 0-1 area (main tile) of the UV map, no
						tiling is allowed. This is because ingame all the LOD textures are combined into a single
						texture called an atlas, so having incorrect uv mapping will end up putting the texture of some
						other random citizen on your LOD.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/uv_lod.jpg" target="_blank"
						><Picture
							width={images.uv_lod.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.uv_lod}
							alt="UV mapping for LOD mesh using automatic mapping in 3ds Max"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">
						UV mapping for LOD mesh using automatic mapping in 3ds Max. No overlap and contained within the
						main tile - good for baking.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="pivot-origin"
			>
				Pivot / Origin
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The pivot point or origin represents the center point on the ground. It's usually represented using a
				red/green/blue axis gizmo.
			</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="transform">
				Transform
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure you are exporting a single mesh, and the associated skeleton, which has the correct rotation
				and scale, as you won't be able to rotate or scale your citizen on import.
			</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="formats">
				Formats
			</h3>
			<ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-inside">
				<li class="mt-4">FBX (2015 or older) (most commonly used)</li>
				<li class="mt-4">DAE</li>
			</ul>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="textures">
				Textures
			</h2>
			<p class="mt-4">These determine the color and material properties of your citizen.</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="resolution"
			>
				Resolution
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">All imported main textures must be the same resolution.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Powers of 2 is a standard practice in 3D graphics, which means sizes such as 512x512, 512x256, 256x256,
				128x256 etc. It is recommended to stick to this standard, but the most important thing is that your
				width and height must be divisible by 32, otherwise, your texture will be corrupted by compression.
			</p>
			<div class="flex items-start justify-start gap-2 mt-6">
				<svg
					class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 text-orange"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m-9.303 3.376c-.866 1.5.217 3.374 1.948 3.374h14.71c1.73 0 2.813-1.874 1.948-3.374L13.949 3.378c-.866-1.5-3.032-1.5-3.898 0L2.697 16.126zM12 15.75h.007v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						Make sure texture quality is set to high in the game's graphics settings. otherwise, your
						imported textures will be downscaled to a lower resolution.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="lod-textures"
			>
				LOD Textures
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				If you don't provide LOD textures, the game will try to bake them using the UV mapping your LOD mesh
				has, and that may cause visual issues, so it's recommended that you create your own LOD textures using
				baking.
			</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="diffuse">
				Diffuse
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>The main color and texture of your asset.</p><p class="mt-4">
						It will look very bright, contrasty, and saturated in the game, so make sure to reduce the
						saturation and limit the brightest parts to a medium/light gray below 140 RGB.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a diffuse map, it will default to white.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/citizen/cittextures.jpg" target="_blank"
						><Picture
							width={images.cittextures.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.cittextures}
							alt="Example diffuse textures for some vanilla citizens"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/></a
					><p class="explanation">Example diffuse textures for some vanilla citizens.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="alpha">
				Alpha
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Transparency, white means opaque or visible, black means transparent or invisible. Gray values
						may affect how it looks from a distance or at an angle.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						If you don't import an alpha map, it will default to fully opaque or fully visible.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha.jpg" target="_blank"
							><Picture
								width={images.textures_alpha.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.textures_alpha}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_alpha_rail.jpg" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.textures_alpha_rail.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.textures_alpha_rail}
								alt="Example alpha texture for some railings and metal beams"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Using lighter values for the invisible parts will decrease the chance of small details like
							railings disappearing completely.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="color">
				Color
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Determines which parts will be affected by color variations. White means fully affected and black means
				not at all.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The diffuse will get multiplied by the color variation, that means the resulting color will look darker
				than the original diffuse.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">If you don't import a color map, it will default to full color.</p>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="specular">
				Specular
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>Reflectivity, black means no reflection and white means max reflection.</p><p class="mt-4">
						The specular highlight from the sun is very big and bright, so you might want to use very low
						(0-10%) specularity for surfaces facing upwards.
					</p><p class="mt-4">If you don't import a specular map, it will default to no specularity.</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/citizen/citspec.jpeg" target="_blank">
							<Picture
								width={images.citspec.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.citspec}
								alt="Example specular map for a roof water tank"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example specular map for a roof water tank.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/building/textures_specular_transition.jpg" target="_blank"
							><Picture
								width={images.textures_specular_transition.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.textures_specular_transition}
								alt="Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map and vice versa"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Transitions between different specular values produce artifacts on the normal map and vice
							versa, even if a normal map is not imported.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="normal">
				Normal
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						Also sometimes called a bump map, adds fake depth or form by affecting how the lighting appears.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						This can be made from the diffuse or a height map (brighter colors will look extruded out more)
						using <Link
							classes=""
							href="http://cpetry.github.io/NormalMap-Online/"
							text="a normal map generator online"
							theme="externallink"
						/>, a photoshop plugin like <Link
							classes=""
							href="http://www.xnormal.net/"
							text="xNormal"
							theme="externallink"
						/>, or standalone software such as <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://www.crazybump.com/"
							text="CrazyBump"
							theme="externallink"
						/>.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						The normal map generator should be set to +X +Y, which means no color channel inversions are
						required.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						High specularity and normal map don't work well together because of the compression, so you
						might want to paint over shiny parts with a solid color before generating a normal map or paint
						over these parts 128,128,255 on the final normal map.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						Read more in the <Link
							classes=""
							href="/normal-maps/"
							text="normal map article"
							theme="internallink"
						/>.
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						If you don't import a normal map, it will default to a flat normal map - no bump.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<div class="">
						<a href="/images/asset/citizen/citnormal.jpeg" target="_blank"
							><Picture
								width={images.citnormal.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.citnormal}
								alt="Example normal map for rocks"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">Example normal map for rocks.</p>
					</div><div class="mt-4">
						<a href="/images/asset/citizen/citnormal2.jpeg" target="_blank"
							><Picture
								width={images.citnormal2.width / 2}
								densities={[1.5, 2]}
								formats={['avif', 'webp']}
								src={images.citnormal2}
								alt="Image shows the same flat normal map on faces with different UV rotation/flip"
								class="w-full h-auto"
							/></a
						><p class="explanation">
							Problem: default normal map value is 0.5, which isn't possible by using 127(left) or
							128(right). Image shows the same flat normal map on faces with different UV rotation/flip.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="format">
				Format
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">Use a lossless format like .PNG.</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The game supports other formats as well, but there is no reason to use another one, it doesn't matter
				how much your texture is compressed or even if it's completely solid or complicated, the game will
				convert it to a DXT format, so the final size won't be affected by anything other than resolution.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				Make sure the texture is 8 bits/channel because a 16 bits/channel image can't be imported. Do not use
				the "Smaller File (8-bit)" feature in the Photoshop Export As window, as that creates an indexed color
				image, not an 8 bits/channel one.
			</p>
			<h2 class="pb-8 mt-24 text-4xl font-medium border-b-2 border-hit-gray-600 text-hit-gray-400" id="import">
				Import
			</h2>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="naming">
				Naming
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The mesh can have any name, but it's not recommended to use spaces or underscores, as the name for the
				lod mesh name will be meshname_lod.
			</p>
			<p class="mt-4">
				The textures must have the same name as the mesh, but with the texture type identifier after it, so the
				result will be names like meshname_d.png and meshname_lod_d.png
			</p>
			<h3
				class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500"
				id="import-folder"
			>
				Import Folder
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>You should place the mesh and texture files in the import folder located here:</p><p
						class="mt-4"
					>
						<span class="path">%LocalAppData%\Colossal Order\Cities_Skylines\Addons\Import</span>
					</p><p class="mt-4">
						The AppData folder is hidden by default, you can access it by copying and pasting the path into
						the file explorer, or pressing <span class="key">Windows + R</span> and typing in appdata.
					</p>
				</div><div class="lg:w-1/3">
					<a href="/images/asset/building/import.jpg" target="_blank">
						<Picture
							width={images.importIMG.width / 2}
							densities={[1.5, 2]}
							formats={['avif', 'webp']}
							src={images.importIMG}
							alt="Files ready for import"
							class="w-full h-auto"
						/>
					</a><p class="explanation">Files ready for import.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="template">
				Template
			</h3>
			<p class="mt-4">The template you choose will determine some things about your citizen:</p>
			<ul class="mt-4 list-disc list-inside">
				<li class="mt-4">AI</li>
				<li class="mt-4">gender</li>
				<li class="mt-4">age phase</li>
				<li class="mt-4">animation</li>
				<li class="mt-4">walk speed</li>
				<li class="mt-4">shader, material properties (color variations)</li>
			</ul>
			<div class="flex items-start justify-start gap-2 mt-6">
				<svg
					class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 text-hoverlink"
					fill="none"
					stroke="currentColor"
					stroke-width="1.5"
					viewBox="0 0 24 24"
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
				>
					<path
						d="M12 9v3.75m9-.75a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0zm-9 3.75h.008v.008H12v-.008z"
						stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
				<p class="italic">
					<em>
						Some of those things can be changed later in the editor itself or using <Link
							classes=""
							href="https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=450877484"
							text="ModTools"
							theme="externallink"
						/> or other mods.
					</em>
				</p>
			</div>
			<h3 class="pb-4 mt-16 text-2xl font-semibold border-b text-hit-gray-400 border-hit-gray-500" id="import-1">
				Import
			</h3>
			<div class="flex flex-col gap-6 mt-4 lg:flex-row">
				<div class="lg:w-2/3">
					<p>
						For citizens, you can't rotate or scale the mesh on import, so you have to make sure it's
						correct in your 3d software or when exporting.
					</p>
